result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Christian D Clyburn in court by video, in custody.   District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court notes that Atty. Katie Kegel was just recently assigned as counsel in this matter from the public defender's office.  Defendant advises that he has not been in touch with the PD's office since he sent them his evaluation form for representation.  As the appointment for counsel was just made today the court is not sure if Atty. Kegel was aware of this court appearance today.  Court next addresses defendant's request for prompt disposition of this matter.  Defendant confirms he has sent in correspondence and is requesting prompt disposition in this matter.  As counsel has not appeared today court will set the matters over to allow time for counsel to appear and discuss the defendant's request for prompt disposition.  Court will also allow bail to be reviewed at the next court date, no written request required.  Court will continue to toll time limits, unless time limits were previously waived.  Clerk of Courts Office to prepare Order to Produce from DCI (note-defendant advises that he may be transfered to another facility prior to the next court date); defendant to be brought over 2-3 days prior so he can meet with counsel.
